article.headline: Late Sparks comeback falls short
article.linkText: Lynx beat Sparks, snap five-game winless streak
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Kristi Harrower had a season-high 15 points,
helping the Minnesota Lynx snap a five-game losing streak with a
76-72 win over the Los Angeles Sparks on Sunday.

Svetlana Abrosimova added 14 points and nine rebounds for the
Lynx (12-14), who led by 20 points at halftime.

Minnesota led 56-31 in the second half, but the Sparks made a
late run.

"We had to prove to our home crowd that we can play together
and, as young as we are, that we can win games like this,"
Harrower said. "We're just a little bit inconsistent at times."

Trailing by double figures with less than 5 minutes remaining,
the Sparks used a 14-1 run to close within two points in the final
seconds.

Mwadi Mabeka's uncontested layup with 12.5 seconds left cut
Minnesota's lead to 74-72. Nicole Ohlde, who finished with 13
points, made a pair of free throws to seal the win.

"Making a nice run doesn't mean anything," Sparks coach Henry
Bibby said. "We didn't come out with any urgency, we didn't have
any intensity and we didn't play any defense early on."

Lisa Leslie led Los Angeles (12-13) with 20 points on 9-of-15
shooting, while Mabeka added 17 points.

Minnesota, playing its first home game since trading star guard
Katie Smith to Detroit, went on a 15-0 run in the first half and
shot 6-for-12 from 3-point range to take a 45-25 lead at the break.
It was the highest first-half point total of the season for the
Lynx.

"We were more effective defensively, which created offense,"
Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "You could see a difference
tonight in the confidence of this team."

Sparks players acknowledged that it was different facing the
Lynx without Smith in the lineup.

"If Katie was in, we would've known where the last shots were
coming from," Leslie said. "Now, you don't know, and I don't
think they did either. You saw that when we got within 10."

Harrower went 3-for-3 from behind the arc for Minnesota, which
earned its first win since July 19.
